GSA workflow tutorial

Fanny Sarrazin

2022-03-01

The goal of this session is to give a flavour of Sensitivity Analysis (SA) by application of several methods to a simple rainfall-runoff model. The uncertain inputs subject to SA are the model parameters. The aim is to assess the impact of the uncertainty in these parameters on the model’s ability to reproduce streamflow observations, as measured by different performance metrics:
- the Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)
- the volumetric bias (BIAS)

The analysis will be conducted using the SAFE(R/Python/Matlab) Toolbox (Pianosi et al., 2015).


Programme

1. Model setup and One-At-a-Time Sensitivity Analysis (OAT).
Load the data and get confident with the rainfall-runoff model (Hymod).

2. Visual and qualitative Global Sensitivity Analysis (GSA).
Perform Monte Carlo simulations (forward propagation of uncertainty): sample the model parameters within their ranges and run the model to obtain an ensemble of runoff predictions. Use a visual and qualitative GSA method for a preliminary assessment of sensitivity (scatterplots).

3. Regional Sensitivity Analysis (RSA).
Use RSA to formally assess the effect of parameter variations on the model outputs (Young et al., 1978; Spear and Hornberger, 1980; Saltelli et al., 2008).

4. Regional Sensitivity Analysis based on grouping.
Use RSA based on grouping to assess the output sensitivity without specifying a single threshold on output values (Wagener et al., 2001).

For further exploration (try another GSA method):

5. Variance-Based Sensitivity Analysis (VBSA). Use VBSA to measure output sensitivity and compare with RSA results (Sobol’, 1990; Homma and Saltelli, 1996; Saltelli et al. 1999; Saltelli et al., 2008; Saltelli et al. 2010).

Throughout the session, we will also examine the impact of several key choices on SA results:
- the threshold value for RSA
- the output (scalar) metric
- the sample size for the Monte Carlo simulations
- the parameter ranges
- the SA method
Further investigation of these choices can be found in Noacco et al. (2019), and a general discussion on the topic is also provided in Pianosi et al. (2016) and in Wagener and Pianosi (2019). The choice of sample size is more specifically discussed in Sarrazin et al. (2016).


The Hymod rainfall-runoff model and the case study catchment

We will use the Hymod model (Boyle 2001; Wagener et al. 2001), that produces a time series of streamflow predictions as output. The model is composed of a soil moisture accounting routine, and a flow routing routine, which in its turn is composed of a fast and a slow routing pathway. Hymod includes 5 parameters:
\(S_M\): the maximum soil moisture (mm) (soil moisture)
\(beta\): the exponent in the soil moisture (-) (soil moisture)
\(alfa\): the partition coefficient (-) (routing)
\(R_S\): the slow reservoir coefficient (-) (routing)
\(R_F\): the fast reservoir coefficient (-) (routing)

The model is applied to the Leaf catchment in the USA (Sorooshian et al., 1983).

The model forcing input data are:
1-year daily observations of rainfall (R) [columns 1 in LeafCatch.txt]
1-year daily observations potential evaporation (PE) [column 2 in LeafCatch.txt]

We will also used output measurements: 1-year daily observations of streamflow (Q) [columns 3 in LeafCatch.txt]

For this application, we can use the following ranges of feasible variations of the parameters:
\(S_M \in\) [0,400] (mm)
\(beta\in\) [0,2] (-)
\(alfa\in\) [0,1] (-)
\(R_S \in\) [0,0.1] (-)
\(R_F \in\) [0.1,1] (-)

1. Model setup and One-At-a-Time Sensitivity Analysis

Load and plot the data (one year of daily observations of rainfall, potential evaporation and flow):

data(LeafCatch)
dat <- LeafCatch[1:365,] # select the first year of data 
warmup <- 30 # set warming-up period

# Plot data:
par(mfrow = c(3, 1),mar=c(4, 5, 0.1, 0.2))
plot(dat[ ,1],type="l",col="blue",ylab="rainfall (mm/day)",xlab = "")
plot(dat[ ,2],type="l",col="blue",ylab="PET (mm/day)",xlab = "")
plot(dat[ ,3],type="l",col="blue",ylab="flow (mm/day)",xlab = "time (days)")

Define the function to simulate the Hymod model:

hymod_sim_workshop <- function(param, rain, evap){ 

## --------------------------
## Recover model parameters:
## --------------------------
Sm <- max(.Machine$double.eps, param[1]) # Maximum Soil Moisture (cannot be zero!)
beta <- param[2] # Exponential parameter in soil routine [-]
alfa <- param[3] # Partitioning factor [-]
Rs   <- param[4] # Slow reservoir outflow coefficient (ratio) [1/Dt]  
Rf   <- param[5] # Fast reservoir outflow coefficient (ratio) [1/Dt] 

N_step <- length(rain) # number of time steps in the simulation horizon

## -----------------------
## Initialize variables:
## ---------------------- 
Pe  <- numeric(N_step) # Recharge from the soil [mm/Dt]
Ea  <- numeric(N_step) # Actual Evapotranspiration [mm/Dt]
sm <- numeric(N_step + 1) # Soil Moisture [mm]
sL <- numeric(N_step + 1) # Slow reservoir moisture [mm]
sF1 <- numeric(N_step + 1) # Fast reservoir 1 moisture [mm]
sF2 <- numeric(N_step + 1) # Fast reservoir 2 moisture [mm]
sF3 <- numeric(N_step + 1) # Fast reservoir 3 moisture [mm]

QsL <- numeric(N_step)  # Slow flow [mm/Dt]
QsF <- numeric(N_step)  # Fast flow [mm/Dt]

# simulation:
for (t in 1:N_step){
    
    # --------------------------
    #   Soil Moisture Dynamics:
    # --------------------------

    FF  <- 1 - ( 1 - sm[t] / Sm )^beta
    Pe[t] <- FF * rain[t] # Compute the value of the outflow 
    # (we assumed that this process is faster than evaporation)
    
    sm_temp  = max(min(sm[t] + rain[t] - Pe[t], Sm), 0) # Compute the water 
  # balance with the value of the outflow 
  Pe[t] = Pe[t] + max(sm[t] + rain[t] - Pe[t] - Sm, 0) + min(sm[t] + rain[t] - Pe[t], 0)
  # adjust Pe by an amount equal to the possible negative sm amount or 
  # to the possible sm amount above Sm.
    
  W = min(abs(sm[t] / Sm ),1) # Correction factor for evaporation
  Ea[t] = W * evap[t] # Compute the evaporation
  sm[t+1] = max(min(sm_temp - Ea[t], Sm), 0) # Compute the water balance 
  Ea[t]= Ea[t] + max(sm_temp - Ea[t] - Sm, 0) + min(sm_temp - Ea[t], 0) # adjust Ea 
  # by an amount equal to the possible negative sm amount or to the 
  # possible sm amount above Sm 
   
  # -------------------------
  #   Groundwater Dynamics:
  # -------------------------
   
  # slow flow
  QsL[t] <- Rs * sL[t]
    sL[t+1] <- sL[t] + (1 - alfa) * Pe[t] - QsL[t]
    # fast flow
    sF1[t+1] <- sF1[t] +  alfa * Pe[t] - Rf * sF1[t]
    sF2[t+1] <- sF2[t] +  Rf * sF1[t] - Rf * sF2[t]
    QsF[t]  <- Rf * sF3[t]
    sF3[t+1] <- sF3[t] +  Rf * sF2[t] - QsF[t]
    
}

Qsim <- QsL + QsF
STATES <- list(sm = sm,sL = sL, sF1 = sF1, sF2 = sF2, sf3 = sF3)
FLUXES <- list(Pe = Pe, Ea = Ea, QsL = QsL, QsF = QsF)
attributes(Qsim) <- list(STATES = STATES, FLUXES = FLUXES)
return(Qsim)
}

Set the parameters to some tentative values, run the model and plot the resulting streamflow time series:

# Set a tentative parameterization:
param = c(200,0.5,0.7,0.05,0.6)
# Run simulation:
flow_sim <- hymod_sim_workshop(param, dat$rain, dat$evap) 
# Plot results:
plot(dat$flow,type="l",col="grey",xlab="time (days)",ylab="flow (mm/day)")
lines(flow_sim,col="black")
legend("topright", legend = c("obs", "sim"),col = c("grey", "black"), lty = c(1))

One-At-a-Time (OAT) effect

Change one parameter - for instance \(alfa\) - and repeat the same steps:

2. Visual and qualitative Global Sensitivity Analysis

In this section, we run Monte Carlo (MC) simulations of the model against a certain number of input (parameter) samples. Each model simulation provides a times series of runoff predictions. To measure the accuracy of each of these times series with respect to observations, we define two aggregate output metrics to be used for the subsequent steps, the Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) and the volumetric bias (BIAS) of the streamflow predictions.

Input (parameter) sampling (this involves a number of choices that will be assessed and revised later on):

# Define input variability space:
DistrFun  <- "unif" # Define parameter distributions
DistrPar  <- list( c(0, 400), c(0, 2), c(0, 1), c(0, 0.1), c(0.1, 1)) # Define parameter ranges
x_labels <- c("Sm", "beta", "alfa", "Rs", "Rf") # Define parameter names (used to customize plots)
M <- length(DistrPar) # Number of parameters

# Choose sampling strategy and size:
SampStrategy <- "lhs" # "lhs" = Latin Hypercube sampling
N <- 150 # Choose the number of samples 

# Perform sampling:
X <- AAT_sampling(SampStrategy, M, DistrFun, DistrPar, N)
colnames(X) <- x_labels
# If you want to see what the sample 'X' looks like:

Definition of summary output metrics:

RMSE <- function(Qs, Qo){ 
   RMSE <-numeric(1)
   RMSE <- sqrt(mean((Qs - Qo)^2)) # RMSE
   return(RMSE)
}

BIAS <- function(Qs, Qo){
   BIAS <-numeric(1)
   BIAS <- abs(mean(Qs - Qo)) # BIAS
   return(BIAS)
}


Check model behaviour by visualising input/output samples with scatterplots

Computation and visualisation of the output metrics:

# Aggregate output time series into various scalar output metric(s):
YY <- matrix(, nrow = N, ncol = 2)
YY[,1] <- apply(QQ[(warmup+1):nrow(QQ),],2,RMSE,dat$flow[(warmup+1):nrow(dat)]) # RMSE
YY[,2] <- apply(QQ[(warmup+1):nrow(QQ),],2,BIAS,dat$flow[(warmup+1):nrow(dat)]) # BIAS

3. Regional Sensitivity Analysis

In this section, we formally assess the sensitivity of the output metrics (RMSE and BIAS) to the model parameters through the Regional Sensitivity Analysis (RSA) method (Young et al., 1978; Spear and Hornberger, 1980; Saltelli et al., 2008). The steps of RSA are:

[1] Choose a threshold value for the output metric(s).
[2] Split the input-output sample into two groups: Behavioural (output value below the threshold) and Non-behavioural (above).
[3] Compare the input sub-samples, for instance by comparing their Cumulative Distribution Functions (CDFs). Sensitivity can be assessed visually or measured quantitatively, e.g. by the Kolmogorov-Smirnov statistic (denoted as KS and which is the maximum vertical distance between the CDFs): \[S_i = \max_q |F_{x_i|x_i \in \mathcal{B}}(q)-F_{x_i|x_i \in \mathcal{N}}(q)|\]

Split sample into behavioural and non-behavioural sub-samples:

# Define the threshold:
threshold = 3.5
# Use the function RSA_indices_thres to split into behavioural (Y<threshold) and non-behavioural (Y>threshold) sample:
rsatr <- RSA_indices_thres(X, Y, threshold)
# To learn what the function 'RSA_indices_thres' does, type:
# ?RSA_indices_thres
# Recover indices of behavioural samples:
idxb <- rsatr$idxb

# Plot behavioural MC simulations:
QQb <- QQ[,idxb]
matplot(QQb, type="l",col="red",xlab="time (days)",ylab="flow (mm/day)", main = paste0("Behavioural simulations with N = ",N, ", ", colnames(Y)," = ",threshold))
lines(dat$flow,col="grey", lwd = c(2))
legend("topright", legend = c("obs", "behav sim"),col = c("grey", "red"), lty = c(1))

Let’s now replot the results with the function scatter_plots highlighting the behavioural parameterizations:

scatter_plots_tr(X, Y, prnam = x_labels, idx = idxb) + ylab(colnames(Y)) + ggtitle(paste0("Behavioural simulations with N = ",N, ", ", colnames(Y)," = ",threshold))

# (red = behavioural, blue = non-behavioural)

Compare the input CDFs of the behaviour and non-behavioural subsample:

# Plot CDFs of behavioural and non-behavioural input samples:
RSA_plot_thres(X, idxb, prnam = x_labels, threshold) + scale_color_manual(values=c("blue","red")) + ggtitle(paste0("CDFs with N = ",N, ", ", colnames(Y)," = ",threshold))

# (red = behavioural, blue = non-behavioural)

3.3 Assess the robustness of the results (i.e. are the results sample independent?)

To assess the robustness of the sensitivity indices, bootstrapping is performed (here Nboot = 1000):

Y = YY[, 1, drop = FALSE] # RMSE

# Define the threshold:
threshold = 3.5

Nboot <- 1000 # Number of resamples used for bootstrapping (recommended value for a rigorous analysis is 1000)
# Assess sensitivity indices with bootstrapping (WARNING: it may take some time to run this line):
rsatr_b <- RSA_indices_thres(X, Y, threshold, flag = 1, Nboot = Nboot, alfa = 0.05) # By adding the extra
# argument `Nboot` to the function `RSA_indices_thres` bootstrapping is performed, 
# 'alfa' is the scalar significance level for the confidence intervals estimated by bootstrapping 

stat_m <- rsatr_b$stat # mean KS over bootstrap resamples
idxb_Nb <- rsatr_b$idxb

stat_lb <- rsatr_b$stat_lb # lower bound of KS over bootstrap resamples
stat_ub <- rsatr_b$stat_ub # upper bound of KS over bootstrap resamples

Here the sensitivity indices with their 95% confidence intervals are plotted.

boxplot1(stat_m, stat_lb, stat_ub, prnam = x_labels)  + ggtitle(paste0("KS with 95% CI, N = ",N, ", \n", colnames(Y)," = ",threshold)) + ylab("KS statistic")

Questions:
Are the sensitivity indices adequately estimated? Is the sample size large enough?

4. Regional Sensitivity Analysis based on grouping

In this section, we assess the sensitivity using the RSA method based on grouping (Wagener et al., 2001). This variant does not require the definition of a single threshold on the output value. It consists of splitting the input factor sample into a given number of groups (e.g. ten) according to the associated output value. In our application, we use ten intervals of increasing output value, designed so to have an equal number of data points in each group. The corresponding ten CDFs are then derived for each input factor. We can apply this method to the input-output sample that we have already created.

Perform RSA based on grouping:

# Select the output metric to be analysed (uncomment option you want to view):
Y_N2 = YY_N2[, 1, drop = FALSE] # RMSE
# Y = YY[, 2, drop = FALSE] # BIAS

# Set number of groups:
ngroup = 10 

# Perform RSA based on grouping:
rsa_gr <- RSA_indices_groups(X_N2, Y_N2, ngroup = ngroup)

# Recover indices of the ten groups:
idx_gp <- rsa_gr$idx
# Recover range of values of the output:
Yk <- rsa_gr$Yk

# Look at the range of values of the output in the ten groups:
Yk
##  [1] 2.267454 2.908424 3.082755 3.230239 3.368403 3.501154 3.612160 3.766976
##  [9] 3.949891 4.212917 8.496640

5. Variance-Based Sensitivity Analysis

In this section, we use Variance-Based Sensitivity Analysis (VBSA) to measure output sensitivities. We compare with the RSA results to assess the effect of the choice of the GSA method.

The key principles of VBSA are:
[a] The variance of the output distribution is a proxy for output uncertainty
[b] Output variance can be decomposed (under broad assumptions) in contributions from individual inputs and their interactions (Sobol, 1990)
\[V=\sum_i V_i + \sum_{i<j} V_{ij} + \sum_{i<j<k} V_{ijk}+...+V_{12...M}\] [c] The variance contribution from an input factor is a measure of output sensitivity to that input. Two indices are commonly used (Homma and Saltelli, 1996):
\[\begin{array}{ll} S_i = V_i/V & \text{First-order (or "main effects") index} \\ S_{T_i} = (V_i + \sum_j V_{ij} + \sum_{j<k} V_{ijk}+...)/V & \text{Total-order (or "total effects") index} \end{array}\]

The first-order index \(S_i\) measures the direct contribution to the output variance from variations of the i-th input. It has the following properties:
i) \(S_i \in [0,1]\)
ii) if \(Si = 0\) then \(x_i\) has no direct influence on \(y\) (but it might still have some in interaction with other factors!)
iii) The higher \(Si\), the larger the direct influence of \(x_i\)
iv) \(\sum_i S_i <= 1\). If \(\sum_i S_i = 1\) then there are no interactions between the factors

The total-order index \(S_{T_i}\) measures the overall contribution from both individual variability of \(x_i\) and its interactions with other inputs. It has the following properties:
i) \(S_{T_i} \in [0,1]\)
ii) if \(S_{T_i} = 0\) then \(x_i\) has no influence at all on \(y\)
iii) The higher \(S_{T_i}\), the larger the overall influence of \(x_i\)
iv) \(\sum_i S_{T_i} >= 1\). If \(\sum_i S_{T_i} = 1\) then there are no interactions between the factors

Approximation of VBSA sensitivity indices. First-order and total-order indices typically cannot be computed exactly, but there are several approximation strategies to compute them from a sample of model inputs and outputs:
[a] FAST and eFAST algorithm, which are based on Fourier transformation of the output (Cukier et al. 1973; Saltelli et al. 1999)
[b] Algebraic approximators based on a “re-sampling” matrix (Homma and Saltelli 1996; Saltelli et al. 2010)
[c] Nonparametric regression approaches (Strong et al. 2014; Stanfill et al. 2015)

Here we will use the second approach [b]. The steps for the algebraic approximation of first-order and total-order indices are:
[1] Generate 2 matrices (XA and XB) of n input vectors each. This can be done using any generic random sampling technique, e.g. Latin-Hypercube or Sobol quasi-random sampling
[2] Generate an additional matrix (XC) of M x n input vectors by resampling from XA and XB. Specifically, each of the M sub-matrices in XC has all the columns of XB but the i-th, which is taken from XA (see Saltelli et al. (2010) for details on resampling)
[3] Execute the model against all input combinations in XA, XB and XC (the total number of model executions thus is (2+M)xn )
[4] Compute 2 x M indices Si and STi (i=1,…,M) as:
f0 = mean(YA)
V = mean(YA.^2) - f0^2
S(i) = ( 1/N *sum(YA.*YC(i)) - f0^2 ) / V
ST(i) = 1 - ( 1/N*sum(YB.*YC(i)) - f0^2 ) / V


Let’s start by resampling. We can re-use the matrix X we have already generated for RSA and split it into the two matrices XA and XB. This has the advantage that we have already executed the model against these matrices, so that we will only have to execute the model against XC.

# Split X into XA and XB, and obtain the resampling matrix XC:
XABC <- vbsa_resampling(X_N2)
# Check input sample dimensions:
dim(XABC$XA)
dim(XABC$XB)
dim(XABC$XC)

# Recover samples corresponding to sub-matrices XA and XB:
YYA = YY_N2[1:(N2/2),]
YYB = YY_N2[((N2/2)+1):N2,]

# Execute the new input samples (XC):
myfun <- "hymod_MulObj" # Function used to compute the model output; to check what this function does, type: 
# ?hymod_MulObj
# Execute the model (WARNING: it may take some time to run this line):
YYC <- model_execution(myfun, XABC$XC, dat = dat)
colnames(YYC) <- c("RMSE","BIAS")

# Select output:
# i_out = 1 # RMSE
i_out = 2 # BIAS
YA = YYA[, i_out, drop=FALSE] 
YB = YYB[, i_out, drop=FALSE]
YC = YYC[, i_out, drop=FALSE]

Check the model output distribution:

Approximate first-order and total-order sensitivity indices using bootstrapping:

# Compute confidence bounds around sensitivity indices:
Nboot <- 1000 # Choose number of bootstrap resamples
ind_vbsa <- vbsa_indices(YA,YB,YC, Nboot)
Si     <- ind_vbsa[1,] # first-order (bootstrap mean)
Si_lb  <- ind_vbsa[3,] # first-order (bootstrap lower bound)
Si_ub  <- ind_vbsa[4,] # first-order (bootstrap upper bound)
STi    <- ind_vbsa[5,] # total-order (bootstrap mean)
STi_lb <- ind_vbsa[7,] # total-order (bootstrap lower bound)
STi_ub <- ind_vbsa[8,] # total-order (bootstrap upper bound)

# Plot main and total effects with confidence bounds:
p1 <- boxplot1(Si, Si_lb, Si_ub, prnam = x_labels) +
ggtitle(paste0("Variance-based Main Effect\n N = ",N2, ", ", colnames(YA))) + ylab("Sensitivity index") + ylim(min(c(min(Si_lb), min(STi_lb)))*1.1, max(c(max(Si_ub), max(STi_ub)))*1.1) 
p2 <- boxplot1(STi, STi_lb, STi_ub, prnam = x_labels) +
ggtitle(paste0("Variance-based Total Effect\n N = ",N2, ", ", colnames(YA))) + ylab("Sensitivity index") + ylim(min(c(min(Si_lb), min(STi_lb)))*1.1, max(c(max(Si_ub), max(STi_ub)))*1.1)
plot_grid(p1, p2, ncol = 2)
